The spec requested \"dot-product over energy/valence/arousal\", but the current `SampleLibrary` schema only stores a single REAL `mood` column. The implementation gracefully degrades to a 1D scalar product.\n- [ ] **Minor — Schema Inconsistency:** `SampleCaptureDaemon` (T-008) uses a 3-column mood schema (`mood_label`, `mood_valence`, `mood_arousal`), while `SampleLibrary` (T-026/T-028) uses a single `mood` column. Since both point to the same `index.sqlite` in production, they will likely collide. This is an integration issue outside the direct scope of `SampleSelector` but critical for system health.\n\n## Verdict: PASS WITH NOTES\n\n## Notes for Lead Agent\n- The \"dot-product over axes\" requirement is technically simplified to a 1D scalar product because `SampleLibrary` only provides a scalar `mood`. This is acceptable given the current state of the library, but be aware that it doesn't actually distinguish between energy/valence/arousal components.\n- There is a major schema collision risk between `SampleCaptureDaemon` and `SampleLibrary`. The daemon uses `mood_valence`/`mood_arousal` while the library expects a `mood` column. You should probably align these schemas in a future task (e.g., update `SampleLibrary` to use the 3-column schema and implement the true dot product).\n- The `avoid_recent` logic is robust and correctly handles dynamic window resizing.\n- Determinism is well-implemented.\n"}}
